Python.name: BubblePancake
Python.correction:
# BEGIN SOLUTION
swapped = True

while swapped:
    swapped = False 

    # Check all pancakes
    for rank in range(0, getStackSize() - 1):
        # When the pancake above is bigger than the next one...
        if getPancakeRadius(rank) > getPancakeRadius(rank + 1):
            swapped = True # We have to check all the pancakes again next time

            flip(rank + 2); # Flip all the pancakes to get the two on top
            flip(2); # Flip the two pancakes to sort
            flip(rank + 2); # Flip all the pancakes back in place


# END SOLUTION

This universe is very simple, with only five functions provided.

int getStackSize()
Returns the size of the stack, that is the amount of pancakes it contains. 
int getPancakeRadius(int rank)
Returns the radius of the pancake passed as argument, with the rank of the top-most pancake being 0. 
boolean isPancakeUpsideDown(int rank)
Returns whether the pancake passed as argument upside-down, that is, if its burned side is on top. As usual, the top-most pancake is of rank 0. 
void flip(int amount)
Flips the amount first pancakes composing the stack, from the top of it. 
boolean isSorted()
Returns whether the pancake stack is correctly sorted.

instructions.en:
Bubble Pancakes

This problem is similar to the previous: you have to sort the pancakes, the smallest at the top and the biggest at the bottom, except you can only flip them to sort.

The purpose here is to sort them using the bubble algorithm, where one pancake is moved to the bottom until it encounters a bigger one. In graphical representations, it looks like a bubble takes the element and move them through the pile. This is where its name comes from.

Now, using pancakes makes it a little more difficult to write, because you have to find a way to swap only two pancakes at a time.

The bubble algorithm consists in browsing the whole pile from top to bottom, and making a comparision between two pancakes. Each time the top pancake is bigger than the one below, you have to swap them, then compare the bigger pancake you just swapped with one below, and so on. You have to browse through the entire pile until no swap has occurred, in which case the pile is sorted.

If you don't understand the basic bubble sorting algorithm, you should try the exercises within the Sorting algorithms lesson. If you do, but can't figure a way to swap only two pancakes at a time, think of a situation where only two pancakes are swapped at a time, and find a way to reach that situation.
instructions.fr:
Crpes et bulle

Cet exercice ressemble au prcdent: il faut que vous triiez les crpes, la plus petite en haut de la pile, et la plus grande en bas de la pile, sauf que vous ne pouvez seulement en retourner quun certain nombre.

L'objectif ici est de trier les crpes en utilisant l'algorithme du tri bulle, o une crpe est dplace vers le bas de la pile jusqu' qu'elle en rencontre une plus grande. Dans les reprsentations graphiques, cela se matrialise par une bulle qui prend un lment et le dplace sur toute la pile, d'o le nom de "tri bulle".

Maintenant, l'utilisation de crpes rend l'algorithme un peu plus difficile crire, car vous devez trouver un moyen d'changer de place seulement deux crpes la fois.

Le tri bulle consiste parcourir la pile entire, de haut en bas, et d'effectuer des comparaisons entre deux crpes. Chaque fois que la crpe du dessus est plus grande que celle du dessous, il faut que vous les changiez, puis que vous compariez la crpe que vous venez de dplacer avec celle du dessous, et ainsi de suite. Vous devez continuer parcourir toute la pile jusqu' que vous ne dplaciez plus aucune crpe, auquel cas la pile est trie.

Si vous ne comprenez pas l'algorithme de tri bulle de base, vous devriez d'abord essayer les exercices le concernant dans la leon "Algorithmes de tri". Si c'est plutt le fait d'changer seulement deux crpes la fois qui vous pose problme, cherchez une situation o seulement deux crpes sont changes, et trouver un moyen d'arriver cette situation.
